id: data-binding
title: Data Communication
---

> In React, data communication between components (parent to child, child to parent, and sibling to sibling) can be achieved through props, state updates, and callback functions or method as a prop.

1. Parent to Child (Props)
    > How: Pass data from the parent to the child component via props.

    ```jsx
    // Parent Component
    function Parent() {
        const message = "Hello from Parent!";
        return <Child message={message} />;
    }

    // Child Component
    function Child({ message }) {
        return <div>{message}</div>;
    }

    ```
2. Child to Parent (Callback Function)
    > How: Pass a callback function from the parent to the child as a prop, and the child calls this function to send data back to the parent.

    ```jsx
    // Parent Component
    function Parent() {
        const handleDataFromChild = (data) => {
            console.log("Data from child:", data);
        };

        return <Child sendDataToParent={handleDataFromChild} />;
    }

    // Child Component
    function Child({ sendDataToParent }) {
        const data = "Hello from Child!";
        return <button onClick={() => sendDataToParent(data)}>Send Data</button>;
    }

    ```

3. Between Siblings (via Parent)
    > How: Lift the shared state to the parent. The parent manages the state and passes it down to both children. A callback function can be used to update the state from one child.

    ```jsx
    // Parent Component
    function Parent() {
        const [sharedData, setSharedData] = useState("");

        const handleUpdateData = (newData) => {
            setSharedData(newData);
        };

        return (
            <div>
            <ChildOne updateData={handleUpdateData} />
            <ChildTwo data={sharedData} />
            </div>
        );
    }

    // ChildOne Component
    function ChildOne({ updateData }) {
        return <button onClick={() => updateData("Data from ChildOne")}>Update Data</button>;
    }

    // ChildTwo Component
    function ChildTwo({ data }) {
        return <div>Received data: {data}</div>;
    }

    ```

### State & Props
> State: State is an internal, mutable data store for a component. It allows components to maintain their own data and re-render when that data changes.

> Props: Props (short for "properties") are inputs passed from a parent component to a child component. They are read-only and cannot be modified by the receiving component.

```jsx 
import { useState } from 'react';

function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  return (
    <div>
      <Count>Count: {count}</Count>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Increment</button>
    </div>
  );
}

function Count({ count }) { 
  return <p>Count, {count}!</p>;
}

```

- <span style={{color: '#ff00a9'}}>State</span> is for managing data within a component.
- <span style={{color: '#ff00a9'}}>Props</span> are for passing data between components.


### Prop Drilling
> Prop drilling is basically a situation when the same data is being sent at almost every level due to requirements in the final level.

> Prop drilling refers to the process of passing data from a parent component to deeply nested child components through multiple levels of intermediary components. This can make the code difficult to maintain and can lead to unnecessary re-renders. 

![][prop-drilling]  

```jsx 
// Suppose you have a Parent component that has a piece of data that Grandchild needs, but Parent passes it through Child to get it to Grandchild.

function Parent() {
  const user = "Alice";

  return (
    <Child user={user} />
  );
}

function Child({ user }) {
  return (
    <Grandchild user={user} />
  );
}

function Grandchild({ user }) {
  return <p>Hello, {user}!</p>;
}
```

* Downsides of Prop Drilling
    - Complexity: Passing props through multiple levels of components can make code harder to read and maintain.
    - Scalability: As your app grows, prop drilling can lead to more complex component trees and increased difficulty managing data flow.
    - Performance: Re-rendering becomes inefficient if multiple intermediate components are updated just to pass props down.

* Alternatives to Prop Drilling
    - Context API: Allows you to create a context object that can be accessed by any component in the component tree without needing to pass props down manually.
    - State Management Libraries: Tools like Redux, Zustand, or MobX can manage state globally, making it accessible throughout your app without needing to prop-drill.

> <span style={{color: '#ff00a9'}}>propTypes</span> is an object that is used to define the expected types of the props component should receive. It is a way to specify the data types and requirements for the props that are passed to a React component.
